o paying.\u003c/p\u003e    \n\u003cp\u003eFortunately, if you do receive an email like this, the claims about the malware and the scammer visiting your house are all bunk. There was no malware, and the scammer will not visit your house—they may not even live in the same country as you. Feel free to delete the email, and remember; paying the scammer only encourages them to send more threats.\u003c/p\u003e    \n\u003cp\u003eForbes also recommends that you \u003ca href=\"https://www.makeuseof.com/blur-your-house-google/\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eblur your house on Google Maps\u003c/a\u003e. That way, if a scammer tries to use a photo of your home in a scam, all they\u0026#39;ll get is a smudged mess.\u003c/p\u003e    \u003c/div\u003e\n    \n        \n\n    \n\n        \n\n\n                \n        \n        \n\n\n        \n\n\n\n\n\n                    \n        \n    \u003c/article\u003e\n\n    \n        \u003c/div\u003e\u003c/div\u003e",
